A Valentine’s Day gift to remember ❤️❤️
How ironic that the day the whole world celebrates love, I get to have an everlasting reminder of love in its purest most unconditional form - my dearest Charlotte. I will never forget thinking, “how can I love another child?” I remember crying throughout my pregnancy tears of guilt for Linda. But when I was in the delivery room and I experienced G-d’s miracles firsthand there wasn’t a question of not having room for love anymore. As I watched my second daughter turn from blue to pink, my heart instantly expanded and welcomed you Charlotte. You made me a mother for a second time and you continue to make me laugh and bring joy into my life. My wish to you on your birthday is that you continue to light up every room with that infectious laugh and smile of yours. I wish you the happiest of birthdays and I hope you have the best my little Charlotta ❤️

Mother’s Day is approaching and I have a few thoughts…
My kids don't have a perfect mom... they just have me. They've seen me try and fail, laugh and cry, brave and weak. I've closed my eyes at night knowing I could have done better and still they love me just the way I am. 
I want to take a second to appreciate my own role as a mother, even though it’s not “Mother’s Day.” Because here’s the thing about moms, it’s a daily thing, not an annual one.
.
#earlymothersday #mothersday2023 #mothersday #mothersdaymay #maythoughts #motherhood #motherlove #momappreciation

As many of you know, it’s not Walter’s third birthday. I had this yearning to cut some of his locks on Lag Baomer even though we couldn’t be in Israel where it’s traditional to bring  3 year old boys for their very  first haircut on this holy day. I thought it would be so overwhelming for my little boy that’s not even three, but on the contrary it was the most incredibly emotional and spiritual day for Walter . Watching him run into the arms of each rabbi with his cute little voice giggling,  saying “thank you rabbi!” That’s what it is for me - something you can’t explain and want to bottle inside forever and ever. He’s turning three and I’m turning 43 on Sunday and this was the best early birthday present anyone could have given to me. I can’t wait for what’s yet to come in the Holy Land as the plans are slowly coming together with the some of the most talented creators in all of Israel: @ruksyevents & @refael_designs for Walter’s upsherin. ✂️✂️✂️

Today I’m celebrating my 43rd birthday and my three beautiful children who made me a mommy - for that alone I love you forever and ever! A wise woman (my mom) always told me, “every day is mother’s day, you’ll see when you’re a mom.” Now that I’m a mama I know what she meant. Today we are-
Celebrating the moms that give it their all even when they don’t think they are.
Celebrating the moms who are no longer with us. 
Women waiting to be moms. 
And all the mother figures in our lives.
Today I’m looking in the mirror turning 43 and feeling blessed to have accomplished the biggest achievement I could have set my goals to be: a mommy to Linda, Charlotte and Walter. The priceless unbreakable bond is one I work at every single day. It’s the best of me. 
Today I’m wishing for every mother to keep empowering each other and spreading love, light, and the wisdoms we need every day. Happy Mother’s Day!

❤️ Jerusalem is always in our heart and prayer ❤️

✨ Netillah symbolizes the purity that begins here, with the Mitzvah of Netilat Yadaym.

...With each Mitzvah, Am Israel shine brighter. ✨

Through Chesed, Tefillah, and Mitzvot we nurture a profound relationship with Hashem, fostering a spiritual closeness that brings us ever closer to the ultimate Geulah.🌊

At the Kotel, we pour out our hearts, seeking divine guidance and offering our deepest hopes and dreams.

It is a place where the past, present and the future converge.⌛

@netillah_inc is proudly present by the Kotel, honoring the Mitzvah of Netilat Yadayim, serving millions of people in the merit of our righteous donors and they loved ones that helped us to make this happen.

...Whether there's a famous person visiting or someone you would never notice, people from all over the world come to this specific place to experience the kedusha it holds.

May we all unite in Chesed, Achdut, and Simcha. Amen!

Postcard From 🌊
📍Dead Sea , Israel 
Please travel near and far for the salt water cure.
How many have you visited the Dead Sea , would love to hear what your experience was like ? 
It’s been told that many have been cured by the dead seas salt Water .
I put walter in but that didn’t go over well #mommytakemeout 
Did you know ?
The Dead Sea is the lowest point on Earth and it is the deepest hypersaline lake in the world. It’s almost 10 times saltier than the ocean, therefore you can float effortlessly on the surface of the water. It’s the most unique experience ever! You can even read a newspaper while you’re floating – how cool is that?

~ What Israel means to me ~
When I step foot on Israeli soil I’m home- it’s not just a visit. I feel G-d everywhere. I know now how it’s the most sacred place on earth. 
It’s very clear to me why my dad would want to selflessly leave only enough money for a cab ride home. 
Our children live better lives.The sweets have a taste you’ll never experience. Those that live in Israel or make Aliya are considered lucky. 
I still remember when I was a little girl, leaving Israel with tears in my eyes as I was leaving back home. People always ask me, “you go to Israel all the time, don’t you want to visit somewhere else?” My answer is always the same. There is no place on earth like Israel.

Happy Father’s Day Shuie
We’ve been blessed with 3 incredible children in the last 6 years and I have watched these little humans become your pride and joy, purpose and the greatest calling of your life. Celebrating the way you love our little bunch.
Keep twirling them, tickling them and keep teaching them things I never knew existed . Let’s Keep holding on to each minute so so tight  and create more memories . You truly have a gift . Fatherhood knew you would make an awesome dad. Seeing  you love them inspires me to be a person & better mom every day. Holding space for every father figure today. The ones who are constant role models. The ones who are praying for their children who need prayers . The mentors. The ones who are patient, loving, present, passionate, fun, and the encouraging. Celebrating you today , we would be lost without you 🫶🏻

I fell in love with you 4 times in my life .
The first time was when I meet you & three times when I watched you embrace fatherhood . 🤍🤍🤍🤍

Five years ago today I found out that I was going to be a mommy for the second time. I was scared to go from one to two. I didn’t know if I would have room to love another baby the same way I love my first. I didn’t know that a mother’s heart could expand to infinity. We dreamed about what she would be like, who she would look like, and now five years later our little Charlotte Sloane is one of the most intelligent and fierce little girls I’ve ever met. And my heart has more than enough love for all of my children.

You’ve been my date for the past 7 years
 I thank G-d for you every day and for the days to come. 
My anniversary reminds me how lucky I am to have Shuie but it also reminds me of the years before I met Shuie. So my anniversary message is to you. To take chances and take a lot of them. Because honestly, no matter where you end up and with whom, it always ends up just the way it should be. Your mistakes make you who you are. You learn and grow with each choice you make. Everything is worth it. Say how you feel, always.
And appreciate every stage you find yourself in in life. Embrace life. There are lessons to be learned and experiences to be had. And the best version of you and your forever will come.

Today is an auspicious day. Today is the yahrtzeit of Rachel Imeinu, a woman so deeply connected to us that she changed the course of history through her tears, prayers, and sacrifices. Rachel Imeinu, whose kever has been visited by hundreds of thousands of Jews throughout the generations. The woman who was promised by Hashem Himself that we would return to the land - the land we are fighting for now - from exile. Rachel Imeinu, our namesake, the mother of the Jewish nation. 

What is courage? Courage is being afraid to do an act upon something, and yet doing it anyways. If we never have the courage to do something then we will never grow. We will never enact change. Rachel had courage. Rachel had courage to give her sister her betrothed. Rachel had courage to be buried away from the other forefathers. Rachel had the courage to advocate for her children on their way to exile. Look at our community now. Having the courage to advocate, unite, and do unimaginable amounts of chessed. 

I don’t believe that anything in life is coincidence.
Today I have the opportunity to speak with the esteemed Jackie Bitton. A night to inspire others during this new reality that we as a collective  nation face. I’m humbled that on the day of Rachel Imeinu’s passing, I, Rachel get the chance to be a “mother” of sorts to our community. Just as Rachel was an advocate for her children, I feel it is my duty to be an advocate for Israel, for the hostages, for those that were brutally murdered in cold blood.

Tonight, I promise to try my best to uphold my personal namesake. As a רחל, as a mother, as a voice in the community. I will try to use my words to inspire and to pray for our holy brothers and sisters in the land that Rachel Imeinu ensured we would return to. To be a light unto nations as Rachel is to this very day. To navigate through these dark moments through unity and unwavering commitment to our heritage that we can navigate the path ahead.

“He can’t change the way he looks but I can change the way I look at him” ~Jackie Bitton

Inspiration=Empowerment
This week I had the incredible opportunity to speak before a large crowd of women who all came out to be inspired and uplifted during this difficult time for Israel and the Jewish nation. 

I always say that I don’t believe anything in life is a coincidence and I discovered that to be true again. Being that it was Rachel Imeinu’s yahrtzeit and my name is Rachel as well, I found it truly humbling to be able to advocate for my people on the yahrtzeit of someone who was and is the biggest advocate for us. I believe that all Rachels have spiritual DNA in them and as my father used to say, “as a Rachel, you have a special responsibility and faith within you.” 

Imagine if a year ago you received an envelope straight from Gd telling you about what is to happen on Oct 7th 2023. What would you do with the unthinkable? How would you prepare yourself? Physically? Emotionally? Mentally? 
Now that tragedy has befallen us, what will you do? 1400 souls would have given anything to have one more day. What are you doing with your “one more day?” Every day is “one more day” of life and how are you spending it? It is not an easy question to answer but what would you do? 

If you had the opportunity to visit Israel right now and assist on the front lines, to go and volunteer around the country, and upon arrival back home everyone asks how it was and for stories,  and if the only thing you saw were the flowers then you have missed the most important takeaway of your life. In ten years, is that the impact that will be left? The “flowers”? Is that what you will remember? We need to be doers not bystanders.

I want to dedicate this post to @meravscloset and @communitychessedfund I have never met such individuals so deeply connected in chessed. It is truly who they are at their core. The most beautiful women and souls. 

May this Shabbos bring you spirituality and rest. Shabbat Shalom! 

~Rachel

We’re about to face 100 days. 100 days since October 7th. 100 days since Hamas destroyed entire families, communities, and WOULD have continued further if given the chance. It’s been 100 days since our brothers, sisters, daughters, and sons, our friends and our neighbors were STOLEN from us- taken hostage into the evil hands of Hamas. We continue to cry to BRING THEM HOME NOW.

When walking through Kibbutz Beeri, it was not like witnessing history in Auschwitz. This is 100 days later, Zaka still on the ground, our soldiers still at war, and the members of this community and so many others still in the hands of the monsters that committed what you can witness yourselves in this video. 

100 days. We did not think we would see this day, and we share this to remind anyone and everyone that it is STILL October 7th until every hostage is returned safely. 

We didn’t silence the video, so listen. This video is of the pre-school. It opens with a colored drawing with chalk on the walls of the school. You can see the sukkah and it’s decorations still up. You can hear the sound of rockets being launched every minute. You can see the total carnage, destruction, and intent of evil in every pixel of this footage. 

Hashem, it’s a new week. Please make it a shavua tov. Please #bringthemhomenow

Bearing 100 days of Bé eri 
Rockets instead of children’s laughter. If you can imagine what that means. They played hide and seek here. They hugged their parents goodbye here and spent their days here with their classmates and teachers. It was a space that was safe, where they were loved, taught about their heritage, and made memories.

As we walked around all we could say was look.. look at the pictures, the projects, the sneakers that still had socks in them. Each piece of art told a story about a beautiful child’s future ripped away.

100 days ago they danced and played and learned and now it’s up to us to be loud, make noise, and make sure that the rest of our nations children are brought home safely.

Their Sukkah’s are still up. The children’s decorations still hang, blowing in the wind. Time is standing still, as we collectively hold our breath for the safe return of the hostages. 

These photos are of hand made decorations out and hanging, and projects we pulled out of the drawers from their classrooms. They weren’t just celebrating the holiday. Simcha Torah. Gan Yeladim. They were LEARNING them. They were learning through art, they were learning through song. Learning as a class, with teachers, and going home with their projects, singing these songs for their parents to listen to. Our own children come home in the beginning of the year, construction paper and glue and googly eyes in their tiny hands for us to decorate our fridge with. Every hostage is someone’s child. Someone’s parent. Someone’s family and friend. It’s still October 7th until every hostage is returned home safely. #bringthemhomenow

A week ago marked 100 days of unthinkable 💔
Today marks the unimaginable October 107 
For how long could you survive the unbearable conditions, without any daylight?
Under difficult conditions and without daylight. In these tunnels, Hamas commits crimes against humanity.
Such a tunnel, in which hostages were held in Gaza, was exposed.
Twenty meters underground, a central space was discovered in which some of the hostages were imprisoned for most of the time. In the space were objects belonging to the hostages, including drawings by five year old Emilia Aloni.
Also found were individual cells with a toilet and mattress behind bars.
Approximately twenty hostages were held at different times in the tunnel, under difficult conditions and without daylight, with minimal oxygen and terrible damp which made breathing difficult.
The hostages are still in captivity in Gaza, under conditions possibly even worse. Among the 136 hostages are elderly men, dependent on medications and assistance.
The world must see and remember this unforgettable testimony of Hamas committing crimes against humanity, and holding children, elderly and ill persons under inhuman conditions.
We must bring them home. Now.
